<!--
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<!DOCTYPE Rule PUBLIC "sailpoint.dtd" "sailpoint.dtd">
<Rule language="beanshell" name="Custom Multi-Attribute Correlation Rule" type="Correlation">
  <Description>
    Ye rule account ko Identity se correlate karta hai using EmployeeID ya Email.
  </Description>
  <Source>                                   -->
  import sailpoint.object.*;
  import sailpoint.api.IdentityService;
  import sailpoint.tools.Util;
  import java.util.HashMap;
  import java.util.Map;
  import org.apache.commons.logging.Log;
  import org.apache.commons.logging.LogFactory;

  // 1. Logging Setup
  Log logger = LogFactory.getLog("custom.rule.correlation");
  Map returnMap = new HashMap();

  try {
      // Account attributes jo source system se aa rahe hain
      String accountEmpId = account.getStringAttribute("EMPLOYEE_NUMBER");
      String accountEmail = account.getStringAttribute("MAIL");

      logger.debug("Correlating account: " + account.getNativeIdentity());

      // 2. Logic A: Employee ID se Match karna (Primary Match)
      if (Util.isNotNullOrEmpty(accountEmpId)) {
          QueryOptions qo = new QueryOptions();
          qo.addFilter(Filter.eq("name", accountEmpId)); // Identity ka 'name' aksar EmpID hota hai
          
          int count = context.countObjects(Identity.class, qo);
          if (count == 1) {
              Identity match = context.getUniqueObject(Identity.class, qo);
              if (match != null) {
                  returnMap.put("identity", match);
                  logger.info("Match mil gaya via EmployeeID: " + accountEmpId);
                  return returnMap;
              }
          }
      }

      // 3. Logic B: Email se Match karna (Secondary Match - Fallback)
      if (Util.isNotNullOrEmpty(accountEmail)) {
          QueryOptions qoEmail = new QueryOptions();
          qoEmail.addFilter(Filter.eq("email", accountEmail));
          
          int emailCount = context.countObjects(Identity.class, qoEmail);
          if (emailCount == 1) {
              Identity match = context.getUniqueObject(Identity.class, qoEmail);
              if (match != null) {
                  returnMap.put("identity", match);
                  logger.info("Match mil gaya via Email: " + accountEmail);
                  return returnMap;
              }
          } else if (emailCount > 1) {
              logger.warn("Duplicate Email mila: " + accountEmail + ". Manual correlation zaroori hai.");
          }
      }

  } catch (Exception e) {
      logger.error("Correlation Rule Error: " + e.getMessage());
  }

  // Agar koi match nahi mila, toh empty map return karega (Account Uncorrelated rahega)
  return returnMap;
  </Source>
</Rule>

/////*
1. account Object Kaha Se Aa Raha Hai?
Jab aap Account Aggregation (ya Refresh) task chalate hain,
toh SailPoint target application (jaise Active Directory, SAP, ya JDBC) se data fetch karta hai.
Aggregation ke dauran, har ek entry (row/record) ek ResourceObject banti hai.
SailPoint us ResourceObject ko account variable ke naam se aapke Correlation Rule ke andar "inject" kar deta hai.
Isliye aapko code mein Account account = ... likhne ki zaroorat nahi padti, wo pehle se waha implicit object ke roop mein maujood hota hai.

2. Kis Source Se Aa Raha Hai?
Ye us Application source se aata hai jiske liye aapne rule likha hai.
Agar aap Active Directory aggregate kar rahe hain, toh account.getStringAttribute("distinguishedName") kaam karega.
Agar aap Database (JDBC) source use kar rahe hain, toh account.getStringAttribute("EMPLOYEE_ID")
(jo aapne SQL query mein column name diya hoga) waha se aayega.

3. Ek Advanced Example (Logic Clear karne ke liye)
Aapne jo code pucha, usme ye data flow aise kaam karta hai:
Java
// Ye 'account' object SailPoint ne ResourceObject se convert karke diya hai
String accountEmpId = account.getStringAttribute("EMPLOYEE_NUMBER"); 
// 'EMPLOYEE_NUMBER' wahi attribute hona chahiye jo Application Schema mein 'Identity Attribute' ya 'Attribute' define hai.

()Correlation Rule ke Important Implicit Objects:-
Jab ye rule chalta hai, toh SailPoint aapko ye 4 cheezein deta hai:-
context: SailPoint API se baat karne ke liye (SailPointContext).
account: Target system ka wo account jo abhi process ho raha hai (Link object ka raw form).
application: Jis application (source) se data aa raha hai uski details.
environment: Current environment ki settings ka map.
*//////
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<!DOCTYPE Rule PUBLIC "sailpoint.dtd" "sailpoint.dtd">
<Rule language="beanshell" name="Custom Environment-Aware Correlation Rule" type="Correlation">
  <Description>
    Ye rule 'environment' map ka use karke check karta hai ki task 'Full' hai ya 'Delta'
    aur uske hisaab se correlation logic badalta hai.
  </Description>
  <Source>
  import sailpoint.object.*;
  import sailpoint.api.IdentityService;
  import sailpoint.tools.Util;
  import java.util.HashMap;
  import java.util.Map;
  import org.apache.commons.logging.Log;
  import org.apache.commons.logging.LogFactory;

  // 1. Logging Setup
  Log logger = LogFactory.getLog("custom.rule.EnvCorrelation");
  Map returnMap = new HashMap();

  try {
      // Account attributes fetching
      String accountEmpId = account.getStringAttribute("EMPLOYEE_NUMBER");
      String accountEmail = account.getStringAttribute("MAIL");
      
      boolean isFullAggregation = false;

      // 2. ENVIRONMENT CHECK: Task ki details nikalna
      if (environment != null &amp;&amp; environment.containsKey("taskDefinition")) {
          TaskDefinition task = (TaskDefinition) environment.get("taskDefinition");
          String taskName = task.getName();
          
          logger.debug("Rule running under Task: " + taskName);

          // Agar task ke naam mein 'Full' word hai (Live systems pe aksar yahi naming convention hoti hai)
          if (taskName != null &amp;&amp; taskName.contains("Full")) {
              isFullAggregation = true;
              logger.info("ENVIRONMENT DETECTED: Full Aggregation mode active.");
          }
      }

      // 3. CORRELATION LOGIC
      
      // Case A: Strict Correlation (Sirf Emp ID se - Full Aggregation ke waqt)
      if (isFullAggregation) {
          if (Util.isNotNullOrEmpty(accountEmpId)) {
              Identity match = context.getUniqueObject(Identity.class, Filter.eq("name", accountEmpId));
              if (match != null) {
                  returnMap.put("identity", match);
                  logger.info("Full Aggregation Match: Found by EmpID " + accountEmpId);
                  return returnMap;
              }
          }
      } 
      
      // Case B: Normal/Flexible Correlation (Emp ID ya Email - Delta ya normal refresh ke waqt)
      else {
          // Pehle EmpID check karein
          Identity match = context.getUniqueObject(Identity.class, Filter.eq("name", accountEmpId));
          if (match != null) {
              returnMap.put("identity", match);
              return returnMap;
          }

          // Agar EmpID nahi mili, toh Email fallback (Flexible logic)
          if (Util.isNotNullOrEmpty(accountEmail)) {
              Identity emailMatch = context.getUniqueObject(Identity.class, Filter.eq("email", accountEmail));
              if (emailMatch != null) {
                  returnMap.put("identity", emailMatch);
                  logger.info("Delta/Normal Match: Found by Email " + accountEmail);
                  return returnMap;
              }
          }
      }

  } catch (Exception e) {
      logger.error("Correlation Rule Error: " + e.getMessage(), e);
  }

  // Kuch nahi mila toh Uncorrelated rahega
  return returnMap;
  </Source>
</Rule>

///////////*
()Zyadatar live systems mein, hum Employee ID ya Network ID (AD Username) ko hi Identity ka name banate hain.
toh yaha name aek keyword hai.ish code me:-Filter.eq("name", accountEmpId).

()3. &amp;&amp; ka kya matlab hai?
Aapne code mein &amp;&amp; dekha hoga. Ye XML ka tarika hai && (Logical AND) likhne ka.
XML files (jo SailPoint Rules hoti hain) mein hum direct && nahi likh sakte kyunki XML parser use error samajhta hai.
Isliye hum Escape Character use karte hain: &amp;&amp;.
Matlab: Agar "Condition A" SAHI hai AUR "Condition B" bhi SAHI hai, tabhi aage badho.

()environment: Current environment ki settings ka map. kya?
--environment ek Map type ka object hota hai jo current system ka runtime environment represent karta hai.
👉 Simple line:-
System abhi kis condition / setup me chal raha hai — uska data = environment.
()Identity management ka behavior bhi environment se control hota hai.


1️⃣ “runtime configuration container”:-
System start → environment banta hai
System stop → environment khatam
ye environment object RAM me store hota hai.

2️⃣ “Map form me”:-
Data key-value pair me store hota hai
Example:-
"env" → "PROD"
"debug" → "false"

3️⃣ “current execution context”:-
Ye bahut important hai ⚠️
Execution context = system abhi kya kar raha hai + kis condition me kar raha hai.
👉 Example:-
Kaunsa task run ho raha hai
Kaunsa user trigger kar raha hai
Kaunsa environment (DEV/PROD)
👉 environment me ye context indirectly ya directly available hota hai.

4️⃣ “operational settings”:-
Ye wo settings hain jo system ka behavior control karti hain:
Logging ka level kya ho
Debugging ON/OFF
Timeout kitna ho
Kaunsa server use ho
👉 Matlab:-
System ka operation kaise chalega — ye define hota hai.

5️⃣ “behavior-controlling parameters”:-
Ye sabse powerful part hai 💥
environment ke values decide karte hain:-
✔ Kaunsa code chalega
✔ Kaunsa skip hoga
✔ Kaunsa resource use hoga

🧠 Example:-
if (env.equals("PROD")) {
    connectRealDatabase();
} else {
    connectTestDatabase();
}
👉 Same code, alag behavior
👉 Sirf environment change se.

7️⃣ “application dynamically control aur adapt kare”:-
Dynamic ka matlab:-
👉 Code change kiye bina behavior change
🧠 Example:-
env value	      Behavior
DEV:-------------testing logic
PROD:------------real logic
👉 Developer ko code change nahi karna,
👉 Sirf config change.

8️⃣ “based on environment conditions”
Conditions kya ho sakti hain:-
Environment type (DEV/PROD),
Server location
Logging level
Runtime flags
👉 System in sab ke basis pe decision leta hai.
-------------------------------------------------
🔹 Iske andar kya hota hai?
Depends system pe, but generally:-
Common keys:-
environment.put("env", "PROD");
environment.put("debug", "false");
environment.put("logLevel", "INFO");
environment.put("timeout", "30");
environment.put("applicationName", "SailPoint");
environment.put("server", "localhost");
👉 Simple language:-
System ke liye rules / settings set ki ja rahi hain jisse wo decide karega kaise behave karna hai.

🔹 Ye actual me kya karta hai?
👉 Ye system ko control instructions deta hai
Jaise:-
Kahan run ho raha hai
Kitni logging karni hai
Kitna wait karna hai
Kis server pe kaam karna hai
👉 Matlab:-
System ka poora behavior in values pe depend karta hai.

🔹TaskDefinition Kab hoti hai environment me?
✅ Jab koi Task run ho raha ho,
Jaise:-
Identity Refresh
Aggregation Task
Custom Task
👉 Tab SailPoint internally environment me daal deta hai:-
"taskDefinition" → TaskDefinition object
👉 Matlab:-
➡ current running task ki info available hoti hai

()🔥 1️⃣ env = PROD:-
env ek environment identifier hai jo system ke execution mode ko define karta hai,
jaise DEV, TEST ya PROD. Jab value PROD hoti hai,iska matlab system live production environment me chal raha hai
jahan real users ka data process hota hai aur saare operations actual business impact create karte hain.
Isliye production mode me security, performance aur accuracy sabse zyada important hoti hai.

🔥 2️⃣ debug = false:-
debug ek control flag hai jo decide karta hai ki system apni internal processing details
(jaise variable values, flow steps, API calls) ko log kare ya nahi.prodme off rakhte hai.

🔥 3️⃣ logLevel = INFO:-
yani system kitni detail me apni execution information record karega.
INFO level ka matlab hai ki system sirf important aur high-level operational messages log karega
(jaise process start/end, major events), bina unnecessary internal debug details ke.

🔥 4️⃣ timeout = 30:-
timeout ek time constraint parameter hai jo define karta hai ki system kisi operation
(jaise API call, database query, external service request) ke response ke liye maximum kitni der tak wait karega.
Yahan 30 seconds ka matlab hai ki agar operation specified time ke andar complete nahi hota,
to system usse fail maan lega aur aage badh jayega, jisse system hang ya indefinitely wait nahi karta.

🔥 5️⃣ applicationName = SailPoint:-
applicationName system ya application ki identity represent karta hai,
jiska use logging, monitoring, debugging aur multi-application environments me differentiation ke liye hota hai.
Jab logs generate hote hain, to ye naam unhe identify karne me help karta hai ki kaunsa application kis event ke liye responsible hai.

🔥 6️⃣ server = localhost:-
server ek configuration parameter hai jo batata hai ki application kis machine ya host environment par run ho raha hai.
----------------------------------------------------------------
🔹 “Current environment ki settings ka map” ka matlab?
Is line ko tod ke samajh:-
✅ Current environment:-
Matlab:-
Abhi system DEV me hai ya TEST ya PROD
Kaunse server pe chal raha hai
Debug mode ON hai ya OFF

✅ Settings:-
Matlab:-
Configurations / parameters / flags
Jo system ka behavior control karte hain

✅ Map:-
Matlab:-
Data key-value format me store hota hai
👉 Final meaning:-
👉 Current system ke sare runtime configurations ek jagah Map me stored hain.
-------------------------------------------------------
()Real flow samajh:-
1. DB / config files me settings stored hoti hain.
2. System start hota hai.
3. Wo settings load hoti hain.
4. Environment Map me daal di jati hain.
5. Code us Map se values read karta hai.
-----------------------------------------------

